Now I can see the issue clearly. Looking at the `gpib_send` function at line 29-53:

```c
void gpib_send(unsigned int gpib_board, unsigned int gpib_device, char *command_string )
{
  unsigned short addlist[2] = {gpib_device, NOADDR};
  SendIFC(gpib_board);

  //Enable all on GPIB bus
  EnableRemote(gpib_board, addlist);


  if(ibsta & ERR) {
    printf("gpib_send: Instrument enable failed! \n");
  }

  //Send Control Commandss
  Send(gpib_board, gpib_device, command_string, strlen(command_string), NLend);

  if(ibsta & ERR) {

    printf("gpib_send: Send failed! \n");

  }

  printf("%s \n",command_string);

}
```

The problem is that this function:
1. Checks for errors after `EnableRemote` (line 38-40) and after `Send` (line 45-48)
2. But it only prints error messages - it doesn't return any error code or status
3. The `calibration` function calls `gpib_send` multiple times but has no way to know if any of them failed

This is a classic case of "missing error propagation" where failures are silently ignored. The errors are detected but not propagated to the caller.

The fix should:
1. Make `gpib_send` return an error code (e.g., return 0 on success, -1 on failure)
2. Update `calibration` to check the return value and handle errors appropriately
3. Update the header file to reflect the new signature

